                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Note on the Declaration for Open Diplomacy</hi>
                    <note n="6" type="source" xml:id="d386fn6">Reprinted from <persName
                            corresp="#p_MDH1">Miller</persName>, <hi rend="italic">My Diary</hi>,
                        vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 154.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-sibling-dates" calendar="gregorian"
                        notAfter="1918-11-30T23:59:59-05:00" notBefore="1918-07-16T00:00:00-04:00"
                        >undated</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>The annexed tentative draft of a Declaration for Open Diplomacy<note n="7"
                        xml:id="d386fn7">
                        <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                    </note> contains provisions for publicity which are made to apply to existing as
                    well as to future treaties and international agreements.</p>
                <p>As regards treaties and international agreements made by a Power at war, the time
                    in which publicity is to be had is extended until thirty days after the
                    conclusion of peace instead of thirty days after the conclusion of the treaty or
                    agreement, but in either case invalidity is the effect of the failure to make
                    public.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
